      "question": "If $7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3 \\cos^2 \\theta = 4$, show that $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}$.",
      "answer": "\\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the identity $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$ to replace $\\cos^2 \\theta$.",
          "Simplify the equation to isolate $\\sin^2 \\theta$ and $\\cos^2 \\theta$.",
          "Divide by $\\cos^2 \\theta$ to get $\\tan^2 \\theta$.",
          "Solve for $\\tan \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3(1 - \\sin^2 \\theta) = 4 \\\\ 7 \\sin^2 \\theta + 3 - 3 \\sin^2 \\theta = 4 \\\\ 4 \\sin^2 \\theta = 1 \\\\ \\sin^2 \\theta = \\frac{1}{4} \\implies \\cos^2 \\theta = 1 - \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{3}{4} \\\\ \\tan^2 \\theta = \\frac{\\sin^2 \\theta}{\\cos^2 \\theta} = \\frac{1/4}{3/4} = \\frac{1}{3} \\\\ \\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}"
      },
